          "body": "The chapter's pastoral center is the cluster of divine names in verse 5: Maker, Lord of hosts, Redeemer, Holy One of Israel, God of all the earth. These are not titles stacked for rhetorical effect; each carries a specific covenantal weight. 'Maker' (*oseh*) grounds God's obligation in creation — He made Zion and is responsible for what He made. 'Husband' (*baal*) names the covenant relationship — Israel's God is not merely patron but spouse, and the marriage metaphor (developed also in Hosea 2, Jeremiah 3, Ezekiel 16) means abandonment was never permanent desertion but marital discipline. 'Redeemer' (*go'el*) invokes the kinsman-redeemer law of Leviticus 25 — God is legally obligated as next-of-kin to buy back what the exile took. 'Holy One of Israel' and 'God of all the earth' frame the covenant in its universal scope: the One restoring Zion is not a local deity defeated by Babylon but the moral Sovereign of all creation. The 'brief moment' of 54:7-8 is theologically precise: the exile was real divine anger but temporally bounded — the disproportion between the moment of anger and the eternity of lovingkindness is the chapter's central pastoral claim."
